<p>The determinant of an <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>n</i> =C3=97 <i>n</i></=
span> matrix can be defined in several equivalent ways, the most common bei=
ng <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Leibniz_formula_for_determinant=
s" title=3D"Leibniz formula for determinants">Leibniz formula</a>, which ex=
presses the determinant as a sum of <span class=3D"mwe-math-element mwe-mat=
h-element-inline"><span class=3D"mwe-math-mathml-inline mwe-math-mathml-a11=
y" style=3D"display: none;"><math xmlns=3D"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/Math=
ML" alttext=3D"{\displaystyle n!}">
  <semantics>
    <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
      <mstyle displaystyle=3D"true" scriptlevel=3D"0">
        <mi>n</mi>
        <mo>!</mo>
      </mstyle>
    </mrow>
    <annotation encoding=3D"application/x-tex">{\displaystyle n!}</annotati=
on>
  </semantics>
</math></span><img src=3D"https://wikimedia.org/api/rest_v1/media/math/rend=
er/svg/bae971720be3cc9b8d82f4cdac89cb89877514a6" class=3D"mwe-math-fallback=
-image-inline mw-invert skin-invert" aria-hidden=3D"true" style=3D"vertical=
-align: -0.338ex; width:2.042ex; height:2.176ex;" alt=3D"{\displaystyle n!}=
"></span> (the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Factorial" title=3D=
"Factorial">factorial</a> of <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-sty=
le:italic;">n</span>) signed products of matrix entries. It can be computed=
 by the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Laplace_expansion" title=
=3D"Laplace expansion">Laplace expansion</a>, which expresses the determina=
nt as a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Linear_combination" title=
=3D"Linear combination">linear combination</a> of determinants of submatric=
es, or with <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gaussian_elimination" =
title=3D"Gaussian elimination">Gaussian elimination</a>, which allows compu=
ting a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Row_echelon_form" title=3D"=
Row echelon form">row echelon form</a> with the same determinant, equal to =
the product of the diagonal entries of the row echelon form.
</p><p>Determinants can also be defined by some of their properties. Namely=
, the determinant is the unique function defined on the <span class=3D"texh=
tml"><i>n</i> =C3=97 <i>n</i></span> matrices that has the four following p=
roperties:=20
</p>
<ol><li>The determinant of the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ide=
ntity_matrix" title=3D"Identity matrix">identity matrix</a> is <span class=
=3D"texhtml">1</span>.</li>
<li>The exchange of two rows multiplies the determinant by <span class=3D"t=
exhtml">=E2=88=921</span>.</li>
<li>Multiplying a row by a number multiplies the determinant by this number=
.</li>
<li>Adding a multiple of one row to another row does not change the determi=
nant.</li></ol>
<p>The above properties relating to rows (properties 2=E2=80=934) may be re=
placed by the corresponding statements with respect to columns.
</p><p>The determinant is invariant under <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.o=
rg/wiki/Matrix_similarity" title=3D"Matrix similarity">matrix similarity</a=
>. This implies that, given a linear <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wi=
ki/Endomorphism" title=3D"Endomorphism">endomorphism</a> of a <a href=3D"ht=
tps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Finite-dimensional_vector_space" class=3D"mw-re=
direct" title=3D"Finite-dimensional vector space">finite-dimensional vector=
 space</a>, the determinant of the matrix that represents it on a <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Basis_(vector_space)" class=3D"mw-redirec=
t" title=3D"Basis (vector space)">basis</a> does not depend on the chosen b=
asis. This allows defining the <i>determinant</i> of a linear endomorphism,=
 which does not depend on the choice of a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.o=
rg/wiki/Coordinate_system" title=3D"Coordinate system">coordinate system</a=
>.
</p><p>Determinants occur throughout mathematics. For example, a matrix is =
often used to represent the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Coeffi=
cient" title=3D"Coefficient">coefficients</a> in a <a href=3D"https://en.wi=
kipedia.org/wiki/System_of_linear_equations" title=3D"System of linear equa=
tions">system of linear equations</a>, and determinants can be used to solv=
e these equations (<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Cramer%27s_rule=
" title=3D"Cramer's rule">Cramer's rule</a>), although other methods of sol=
ution are computationally much more efficient. Determinants are used for de=
fining the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Characteristic_polynomi=
al" title=3D"Characteristic polynomial">characteristic polynomial</a> of a =
square matrix, whose roots are the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki=
/Eigenvalue" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Eigenvalue">eigenvalues</a>. In=
 <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Geometry" title=3D"Geometry">geom=
etry</a>, the signed <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-style:itali=
c;">n</span>-dimensional <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Volume" t=
itle=3D"Volume">volume</a> of a <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" style=3D"font-=
style:italic;">n</span>-dimensional <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wik=
i/Parallelepiped" title=3D"Parallelepiped">parallelepiped</a> is expressed =
by a determinant, and the determinant of a linear <a href=3D"https://en.wik=
ipedia.org/wiki/Endomorphism" title=3D"Endomorphism">endomorphism</a> deter=
mines how the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Orientability" title=
=3D"Orientability">orientation</a> and the <span class=3D"texhtml mvar" sty=
le=3D"font-style:italic;">n</span>-dimensional volume are transformed under=
 the endomorphism. This is used in <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki=
/Calculus" title=3D"Calculus">calculus</a> with <a href=3D"https://en.wikip=
edia.org/wiki/Exterior_differential_form" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Ex=
terior differential form">exterior differential forms</a> and the <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jacobian_determinant" class=3D"mw-redirec=
t" title=3D"Jacobian determinant">Jacobian determinant</a>, in particular f=
or <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Integration_by_substitution#Sub=
stitution_for_multiple_variables" title=3D"Integration by substitution">cha=
nges of variables</a> in <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Multiple_=
integral" title=3D"Multiple integral">multiple integrals</a>.
</p>
