<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Geometric_meaning">Geometri=
c meaning</h2><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-=
bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DDe=
terminant&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D3" title=3D"Edit section: Geometr=
ic meaning"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</=
span></span></div>
<figure class=3D"mw-default-size mw-halign-right" typeof=3D"mw:File/Thumb">=
<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Area_parallelogram_as_determi=
nant_modified.svg" class=3D"mw-file-description"><img src=3D"https://upload=
.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/9/98/Area_parallelogram_as_determina=
nt_modified.svg/250px-Area_parallelogram_as_determinant_modified.svg.png" d=
ecoding=3D"async" width=3D"250" height=3D"287" class=3D"mw-file-element" da=
ta-file-width=3D"870" data-file-height=3D"1000"></a><figcaption>The area of=
 the parallelogram is the absolute value of the determinant of the matrix f=
ormed by the vectors representing the parallelogram's sides.</figcaption></=
figure>
<p>If the matrix entries are real numbers, the matrix <span class=3D"texhtm=
l">A</span> represents the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Linear_=
map" title=3D"Linear map">linear map</a> that maps the <a href=3D"https://e=
n.wikipedia.org/wiki/Basis_vector" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Basis vec=
tor">basis vectors</a> to the columns of <span class=3D"texhtml">A</span>. =
 The images of the basis vectors form a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org=
/wiki/Parallelogram" title=3D"Parallelogram">parallelogram</a> that represe=
nts the image of the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Unit_square" =
title=3D"Unit square">unit square</a> under the mapping.  The parallelogram=
 defined by the columns of the above matrix is the one with vertices at <sp=
an class=3D"texhtml">(0, 0)</span>, <span class=3D"texhtml">(<i>a</i>, <i>c=
</i>)</span>, <span class=3D"texhtml">(<i>a</i> + <i>b</i>, <i>c</i> + <i>d=
</i>)</span>, and <span class=3D"texhtml">(<i>b</i>, <i>d</i>)</span>, as s=
hown in the accompanying diagram.
</p><p>The absolute value of <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>ad</i> =E2=88=92 <i=
>bc</i></span> is the area of the parallelogram, and thus represents the sc=
ale factor by which areas are transformed by <span class=3D"texhtml">A</spa=
n>.
</p><p>The absolute value of the determinant together with the sign becomes=
 the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Signed_area" title=3D"Signed =
area">signed area</a> of the parallelogram. The signed area is the same as =
the usual <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Area_(geometry)" class=
=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Area (geometry)">area</a>, except that it is nega=
tive when the angle from the first to the second vector defining the parall=
elogram turns in a clockwise direction (which is opposite to the direction =
one would get for the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Identity_mat=
rix" title=3D"Identity matrix">identity matrix</a>).
</p><p>To show that <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>ad</i> =E2=88=92 <i>bc</i></=
span> is the signed area, one may consider a matrix containing two vectors =
<span class=3D"texhtml"><b>u</b> =E2=89=A1 (<i>a</i>, <i>c</i>)</span> and =
<span class=3D"texhtml"><b>v</b> =E2=89=A1 (<i>b</i>, <i>d</i>)</span> repr=
esenting the parallelogram's sides. The signed area can be expressed as <sp=
