<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"History">History</h2><span =
class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a =
href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DDeterminant&amp;action=
=3Dedit&amp;section=3D25" title=3D"Edit section: History"><span>edit</span>=
</a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>Historically, determinants were used long before matrices: A determinant=
 was originally defined as a property of a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.=
org/wiki/System_of_linear_equations" title=3D"System of linear equations">s=
ystem of linear equations</a>.
The determinant "determines" whether the system has a unique solution (whic=
h occurs precisely if the determinant is non-zero).
In this sense, determinants were first used in the Chinese mathematics text=
book <i><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Nine_Chapters_on_the_M=
athematical_Art" title=3D"The Nine Chapters on the Mathematical Art">The Ni=
ne Chapters on the Mathematical Art</a></i> (=E4=B9=9D=E7=AB=A0=E7=AE=97=E8=
=A1=93, Chinese scholars, around the 3rd century BCE). In Europe, solutions=
 of linear systems of two equations were expressed by <a href=3D"https://en=
.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gerolamo_Cardano" title=3D"Gerolamo Cardano">Cardano</a=
> in 1545 by a determinant-like entity.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-21" class=3D"ref=
erence"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Determinant#cite_note-21">=
<span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>21<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span=
></a></sup>
</p><p>Determinants proper originated separately from the work of <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Seki_Takakazu" title=3D"Seki Takakazu">Se=
ki Takakazu</a> in 1683 in Japan and parallelly of <a href=3D"https://en.wi=
kipedia.org/wiki/Gottfried_Leibniz" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Gottfrie=
d Leibniz">Leibniz</a> in 1693.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-22" class=3D"reference">=
<a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Determinant#cite_note-22"><span cl=
ass=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>22<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></s=
up><sup id=3D"cite_ref-Campbell_23-0" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https:=
//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Determinant#cite_note-Campbell-23"><span class=3D"c=
ite-bracket">[</span>23<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup =
id=3D"cite_ref-24" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/=
wiki/Determinant#cite_note-24"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>24<span=
 class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-25" class=3D"=
reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Determinant#cite_note-2=
5"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>25<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</s=
pan></a></sup> <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Determinant#CITEREF=
Cramer1750">Cramer (1750)</a> stated, without proof, Cramer's rule.<sup id=
=3D"cite_ref-26" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wi=
ki/Determinant#cite_note-26"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>26<span c=
lass=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> Both Cramer and also <a href=3D"ht=
tps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Determinant#CITEREFB%C3%A9zout1779">B=C3=A9zout=
 (1779)</a> were led to determinants by the question of <a href=3D"https://=
en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Plane_curve" title=3D"Plane curve">plane curves</a> p=
assing through a given set of points.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-27" class=3D"refer=
ence"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Determinant#cite_note-27"><s=
pan class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>27<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span><=
/a></sup>
</p><p><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Vandermonde" class=3D"mw-re=
direct" title=3D"Vandermonde">Vandermonde</a> (1771) first recognized deter=
minants as independent functions.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Campbell_23-1" class=
=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Determinant#cite_no=
te-Campbell-23"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>23<span class=3D"cite-=
bracket">]</span></a></sup> <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Determ=
inant#CITEREFLaplace1772">Laplace (1772)</a> gave the general method of exp=
anding a determinant in terms of its complementary <a href=3D"https://en.wi=
kipedia.org/wiki/Minor_(matrix)" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Minor (matr=
ix)">minors</a>: Vandermonde had already given a special case.<sup id=3D"ci=
te_ref-28" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Det=
erminant#cite_note-28"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>28<span class=
=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> Immediately following, <a href=3D"http=
s://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Joseph_Louis_Lagrange" class=3D"mw-redirect" titl=
e=3D"Joseph Louis Lagrange">Lagrange</a> (1773) treated determinants of the=
 second and third order and applied it to questions of <a href=3D"https://e=
n.wikipedia.org/wiki/Elimination_theory" title=3D"Elimination theory">elimi=
nation theory</a>; he proved many special cases of general identities.
</p><p><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Carl_Friedrich_Gauss" title=
=3D"Carl Friedrich Gauss">Gauss</a> (1801) made the next advance. Like Lagr=
ange, he made much use of determinants in the <a href=3D"https://en.wikiped=
ia.org/wiki/Theory_of_numbers" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Theory of num=
bers">theory of numbers</a>. He introduced the word "determinant" (Laplace =
had used "resultant"), though not in the present signification, but rather =
as applied to the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Discriminant" ti=
tle=3D"Discriminant">discriminant</a> of a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.=
org/wiki/Quadratic_form" title=3D"Quadratic form">quadratic form</a>.<sup i=
d=3D"cite_ref-29" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w=
iki/Determinant#cite_note-29"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>29<span =
class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> Gauss also arrived at the notion =
of reciprocal (inverse) determinants, and came very near the multiplication=
 theorem.<sup class=3D"noprint Inline-Template" style=3D"margin-left:0.1em;=
 white-space:nowrap;">[<i><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wikipedi=
a:Please_clarify" title=3D"Wikipedia:Please clarify"><span title=3D"What is=
 &quot;the multiplication theorem&quot;? (June 2023)">clarification needed<=
/span></a></i>]</sup>
</p><p>The next contributor of importance is <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedi=
a.org/wiki/Jacques_Philippe_Marie_Binet" title=3D"Jacques Philippe Marie Bi=
net">Binet</a> (1811, 1812), who formally stated the theorem relating to th=
e product of two matrices of <i>m</i> columns and <i>n</i> rows, which for =
the special case of <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>m</i> =3D <i>n</i></span> re=
duces to the multiplication theorem. On the same day (November 30, 1812) th=
at Binet presented his paper to the Academy, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedi=
a.org/wiki/Cauchy" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Cauchy">Cauchy</a> also p=
resented one on the subject. (See <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/=
Cauchy%E2%80%93Binet_formula" title=3D"Cauchy=E2=80=93Binet formula">Cauchy=
=E2=80=93Binet formula</a>.) In this he used the word "determinant" in its =
present sense,<sup id=3D"cite_ref-30" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https:=
//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Determinant#cite_note-30"><span class=3D"cite-brack=
et">[</span>30<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cit=
e_ref-31" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dete=
rminant#cite_note-31"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>31<span class=3D=
"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> summarized and simplified what was then k=
nown on the subject, improved the notation, and gave the multiplication the=
orem with a proof more satisfactory than Binet's.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-Campbe=
ll_23-2" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Deter=
minant#cite_note-Campbell-23"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>23<span =
class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-32" class=3D"r=
eference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Determinant#cite_note-32=
"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>32<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</sp=
an></a></sup> With him begins the theory in its generality.
</p><p><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Determinant#CITEREFJacobi18=
41">Jacobi (1841)</a> used the functional determinant which Sylvester later=
 called the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jacobian_matrix_and_de=
terminant" title=3D"Jacobian matrix and determinant">Jacobian</a>.<sup id=
=3D"cite_ref-33" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wi=
ki/Determinant#cite_note-33"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>33<span c=
lass=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> In his memoirs in <i><a href=3D"ht=
tps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Crelle%27s_Journal" title=3D"Crelle's Journal">=
Crelle's Journal</a></i> for 1841 he specially treats this subject, as well=
 as the class of alternating functions which Sylvester has called <i>altern=
ants</i>. About the time of Jacobi's last memoirs, <a href=3D"https://en.wi=
kipedia.org/wiki/James_Joseph_Sylvester" title=3D"James Joseph Sylvester">S=
ylvester</a> (1839) and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Arthur_Cay=
ley" title=3D"Arthur Cayley">Cayley</a> began their work. <a href=3D"https:=
//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Determinant#CITEREFCayley1841">Cayley 1841</a> intr=
oduced the modern notation for the determinant using vertical bars.<sup id=
=3D"cite_ref-34" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wi=
ki/Determinant#cite_note-34"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>34<span c=
lass=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup><sup id=3D"cite_ref-35" class=3D"re=
ference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Determinant#cite_note-35"=
><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>35<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</spa=
n></a></sup>
</p><p>The study of special forms of determinants has been the natural resu=
lt of the completion of the general theory. Axisymmetric determinants have =
been studied by <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lebesgue" class=3D=
"mw-redirect" title=3D"Lebesgue">Lebesgue</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipe=
dia.org/wiki/Otto_Hesse" title=3D"Otto Hesse">Hesse</a>, and Sylvester; <a =
href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Persymmetric" class=3D"mw-redirect" t=
itle=3D"Persymmetric">persymmetric</a> determinants by Sylvester and <a hre=
f=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hermann_Hankel" title=3D"Hermann Hankel"=
>Hankel</a>; <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Circulant" class=3D"m=
w-redirect" title=3D"Circulant">circulants</a> by <a href=3D"https://en.wik=
ipedia.org/wiki/Eug%C3%A8ne_Charles_Catalan" title=3D"Eug=C3=A8ne Charles C=
atalan">Catalan</a>, <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/William_Spott=
iswoode" title=3D"William Spottiswoode">Spottiswoode</a>, <a href=3D"https:=
//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/James_Whitbread_Lee_Glaisher" title=3D"James Whitbr=
ead Lee Glaisher">Glaisher</a>, and Scott; skew determinants and <a href=3D=
"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pfaffian" title=3D"Pfaffian">Pfaffians</a>, =
in connection with the theory of <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/O=
rthogonal_transformation" title=3D"Orthogonal transformation">orthogonal tr=
ansformation</a>, by Cayley; continuants by Sylvester; <a href=3D"https://e=
n.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wronskian" title=3D"Wronskian">Wronskians</a> (so call=
ed by <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Thomas_Muir_(mathematician)"=
 title=3D"Thomas Muir (mathematician)">Muir</a>) by <a href=3D"https://en.w=
ikipedia.org/wiki/Elwin_Bruno_Christoffel" title=3D"Elwin Bruno Christoffel=
">Christoffel</a> and <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ferdinand_Ge=
org_Frobenius" title=3D"Ferdinand Georg Frobenius">Frobenius</a>; compound =
determinants by Sylvester, Reiss, and Picquet; Jacobians and <a href=3D"htt=
ps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hessian_matrix" title=3D"Hessian matrix">Hessian=
s</a> by Sylvester; and symmetric gauche determinants by <a href=3D"https:/=
/en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Trudi" title=3D"Trudi">Trudi</a>. Of the textbooks o=
n the subject Spottiswoode's was the first. In America, Hanus (1886), Weld =
(1893), and Muir/Metzler (1933) published treatises.
</p>
