<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Orientation_of_a_basis">Ori=
entation of a basis</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-ed=
itsection-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?=
title=3DDeterminant&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D30" title=3D"Edit secti=
on: Orientation of a basis"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsect=
ion-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<link rel=3D"mw-deduplicated-inline-style" href=3D"mw-data:TemplateStyles:r=
1320445320"><div role=3D"note" class=3D"hatnote navigation-not-searchable">=
Main article: <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Orientation_(vector_=
space)" title=3D"Orientation (vector space)">Orientation (vector space)</a>=
</div>
<p>The determinant can be thought of as assigning a number to every <a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sequence" title=3D"Sequence">sequence</a>=
 of <i>n</i> vectors in <b>R</b><sup><i>n</i></sup>, by using the square ma=
trix whose columns are the given vectors. The determinant will be nonzero i=
f and only if the sequence of vectors is a <i>basis</i> for <b>R</b><sup><i=
>n</i></sup>. In that case, the sign of the determinant determines whether =
the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Orientation_(vector_space)" ti=
tle=3D"Orientation (vector space)">orientation</a> of the basis is consiste=
nt with or opposite to the orientation of the <a href=3D"https://en.wikiped=
ia.org/wiki/Standard_basis" title=3D"Standard basis">standard basis</a>. In=
 the case of an orthogonal basis, the magnitude of the determinant is equal=
 to the <i>product</i> of the lengths of the basis vectors.  For instance, =
an <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Orthogonal_matrix" title=3D"Ort=
hogonal matrix">orthogonal matrix</a> with entries in <b>R</b><sup><i>n</i>=
</sup> represents an <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Orthonormal_b=
asis" title=3D"Orthonormal basis">orthonormal basis</a> in <a href=3D"https=
://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Euclidean_space" title=3D"Euclidean space">Euclide=
an space</a>, and hence has determinant of =C2=B11 (since all the vectors h=
ave length 1). The determinant is +1 if and only if the basis has the same =
orientation. It is =E2=88=921 if and only if the basis has the opposite ori=
entation.
</p><p>More generally, if the determinant of <i>A</i> is positive, <i>A</i>=
 represents an orientation-preserving <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w=
iki/Linear_transformation" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Linear transforma=
tion">linear transformation</a> (if <i>A</i> is an orthogonal <span class=
=3D"texhtml">2 =C3=97 2</span> or <span class=3D"texhtml">3 =C3=97 3</span>=
 matrix, this is a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rotation_(mathe=
matics)" title=3D"Rotation (mathematics)">rotation</a>), while if it is neg=
ative, <i>A</i> switches the orientation of the basis.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Volume_and_Jacobian_determi=
nant">Volume and Jacobian determinant</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><s=
pan class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedi=
a.org/w/index.php?title=3DDeterminant&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D31" t=
itle=3D"Edit section: Volume and Jacobian determinant"><span>edit</span></a=
><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>As pointed out above, the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Absol=
ute_value" title=3D"Absolute value">absolute value</a> of the determinant o=
f real vectors is equal to the volume of the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedi=
a.org/wiki/Parallelepiped" title=3D"Parallelepiped">parallelepiped</a> span=
ned by those vectors. As a consequence, if <span class=3D"mwe-math-element =
mwe-math-element-inline"><span class=3D"mwe-math-mathml-inline mwe-math-mat=
hml-a11y" style=3D"display: none;"><math xmlns=3D"http://www.w3.org/1998/Ma=
th/MathML" alttext=3D"{\displaystyle f:\mathbf {R} ^{n}\to \mathbf {R} ^{n}=
}">
  <semantics>
    <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
      <mstyle displaystyle=3D"true" scriptlevel=3D"0">
        <mi>f</mi>
        <mo>:</mo>
        <msup>
          <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
            <mi mathvariant=3D"bold">R</mi>
