<p>Another infinite-dimensional notion of determinant is the <a href=3D"htt=
ps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Functional_determinant" title=3D"Functional dete=
rminant">functional determinant</a>.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Operators_in_von_Neumann_al=
gebras">Operators in von Neumann algebras</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection=
"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wiki=
pedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DDeterminant&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D4=
1" title=3D"Edit section: Operators in von Neumann algebras"><span>edit</sp=
an></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div>
<p>For operators in a finite <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Von_N=
eumann_algebra#Factors" title=3D"Von Neumann algebra">factor</a>, one may d=
efine a positive real-valued determinant called the <a href=3D"https://en.w=
ikipedia.org/wiki/Fuglede%E2%88%92Kadison_determinant" title=3D"Fuglede=E2=
=88=92Kadison determinant">Fuglede=E2=88=92Kadison determinant</a> using th=
e canonical trace. In fact, corresponding to every <a href=3D"https://en.wi=
kipedia.org/wiki/State_(functional_analysis)#tracial_state" title=3D"State =
(functional analysis)">tracial state</a> on a <a href=3D"https://en.wikiped=
ia.org/wiki/Von_Neumann_algebra" title=3D"Von Neumann algebra">von Neumann =
algebra</a> there is a notion of Fuglede=E2=88=92Kadison determinant.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Related_notions_for_non-com=
mutative_rings">Related notions for non-commutative rings</h3><span class=
=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</span><a href=
=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DDeterminant&amp;action=3De=
dit&amp;section=3D42" title=3D"Edit section: Related notions for non-commut=
ative rings"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]<=
/span></span></div>
<p>For matrices over non-commutative rings, multilinearity and alternating =
properties are incompatible for <span class=3D"texhtml"><i>n</i> =E2=89=A5 =
2</span>,<sup id=3D"cite_ref-48" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.=
wikipedia.org/wiki/Determinant#cite_note-48"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[=
</span>48<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> so there is no goo=
d definition of the determinant in this setting.
</p><p>For square matrices with entries in a non-commutative ring, there ar=
e various difficulties in defining determinants analogously to that for com=
mutative rings. A meaning can be given to the Leibniz formula provided that=
 the order for the product is specified, and similarly for other definition=
s of the determinant, but non-commutativity then leads to the loss of many =
fundamental properties of the determinant, such as the multiplicative prope=
rty or that the determinant is unchanged under transposition of the matrix.=
 Over non-commutative rings, there is no reasonable notion of a multilinear=
 form (existence of a nonzero <span class=3D"clarify-content" style=3D"padd=
ing-left:0.1em; padding-right:0.1em; color:var(--color-subtle, #54595d); bo=
rder:1px solid var(--border-color-subtle, #c8ccd1);">bilinear form</span><s=
up class=3D"noprint Inline-Template Template-Clarify" style=3D"margin-left:=
0.1em; white-space:nowrap;">[<i><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wi=
kipedia:Please_clarify" title=3D"Wikipedia:Please clarify"><span title=3D"W=
hat exactly is meant by this term must be specified. This statement is vali=
d only if the bilinear form is required to be linear on the same side for b=
oth arguments; in contrast, Bourbaki defines a bilinear form B as having th=
e property B(ax,yb) =3D aB(x,y)b, i.e., left-linear in the left argument an=
d right-linear in the other. (October 2017)">clarify</span></a></i>]</sup> =
with a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Regular_element_(ring_theor=
y)" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Regular element (ring theory)">regular e=
lement</a> of <i>R</i> as value on some pair of arguments implies that <i>R=
</i> is commutative). Nevertheless, various notions of non-commutative dete=
rminant have been formulated that preserve some of the properties of determ=
inants, notably <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Quasideterminant" =
title=3D"Quasideterminant">quasideterminants</a> and the <a href=3D"https:/=
/en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dieudonn%C3%A9_determinant" title=3D"Dieudonn=C3=A9 =
determinant">Dieudonn=C3=A9 determinant</a>. For some classes of matrices w=
ith non-commutative elements, one can define the determinant and prove line=
ar algebra theorems that are very similar to their commutative analogs. Exa=
mples include the <i>q</i>-determinant on quantum groups, the <a href=3D"ht=
tps://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Capelli_determinant" class=3D"mw-redirect" titl=
e=3D"Capelli determinant">Capelli determinant</a> on Capelli matrices, and =
the <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Berezinian" title=3D"Berezinia=
n">Berezinian</a> on <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Supermatrices=
" class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Supermatrices">supermatrices</a> (i.e., ma=
trices whose entries are elements of <span class=3D"mwe-math-element mwe-ma=
th-element-inline"><span class=3D"mwe-math-mathml-inline mwe-math-mathml-a1=
1y" style=3D"display: none;"><math xmlns=3D"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/Mat=
hML" alttext=3D"{\displaystyle \mathbb {Z} _{2}}">
  <semantics>
    <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
      <mstyle displaystyle=3D"true" scriptlevel=3D"0">
        <msub>
          <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
            <mi mathvariant=3D"double-struck">Z</mi>
          </mrow>
          <mrow class=3D"MJX-TeXAtom-ORD">
            <mn>2</mn>
          </mrow>
        </msub>
      </mstyle>
    </mrow>
    <annotation encoding=3D"application/x-tex">{\displaystyle \mathbb {Z} _=
{2}}</annotation>
  </semantics>
</math></span><img src=3D"https://wikimedia.org/api/rest_v1/media/math/rend=
