"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Determinant#cite_note-=
49"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>49<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</=
span></a></sup> <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Manin_matrices" cl=
ass=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Manin matrices">Manin matrices</a> form the cl=
ass closest to matrices with commutative elements.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading2"><h2 id=3D"Calculation">Calculation</h=
2><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">[</=
span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?title=3DDeterminant&am=
p;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D43" title=3D"Edit section: Calculation"><span=
>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-bracket">]</span></span></div=
>
<p>Determinants are mainly used as a theoretical tool. They are rarely calc=
ulated explicitly in <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Numerical_lin=
ear_algebra" title=3D"Numerical linear algebra">numerical linear algebra</a=
>, where for applications such as checking invertibility and finding eigenv=
alues the determinant has largely been supplanted by other techniques.<sup =
id=3D"cite_ref-50" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/=
wiki/Determinant#cite_note-50"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">[</span>50<span=
 class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup> <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.=
org/wiki/Computational_geometry" title=3D"Computational geometry">Computati=
onal geometry</a>, however, does frequently use calculations related to det=
erminants.<sup id=3D"cite_ref-51" class=3D"reference"><a href=3D"https://en=
.wikipedia.org/wiki/Determinant#cite_note-51"><span class=3D"cite-bracket">=
[</span>51<span class=3D"cite-bracket">]</span></a></sup>
</p><p>While the determinant can be computed directly using the Leibniz rul=
e this approach is extremely inefficient for large matrices, since that for=
mula requires calculating <span class=3D"mwe-math-element mwe-math-element-=
inline"><span class=3D"mwe-math-mathml-inline mwe-math-mathml-a11y" style=
=3D"display: none;"><math xmlns=3D"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" altt=
ext=3D"{\displaystyle n!}">
