<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Gaussian_elimination">Gauss=
ian elimination</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-editse=
ction-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?titl=
e=3DDeterminant&amp;action=3Dedit&amp;section=3D44" title=3D"Edit section: =
Gaussian elimination"><span>edit</span></a><span class=3D"mw-editsection-br=
acket">]</span></span></div>
<p><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gaussian_elimination" title=3D"=
Gaussian elimination">Gaussian elimination</a> consists of left multiplying=
 a matrix by <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Elementary_matrices" =
class=3D"mw-redirect" title=3D"Elementary matrices">elementary matrices</a>=
 for getting a matrix in a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Row_ech=
elon_form" title=3D"Row echelon form">row echelon form</a>. One can restric=
t the computation to elementary matrices of determinant <span class=3D"texh=
tml">1</span>. In this case, the determinant of the resulting row echelon f=
orm equals the determinant of the initial matrix. As a row echelon form is =
a <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Triangular_matrix" title=3D"Tria=
ngular matrix">triangular matrix</a>, its determinant is the product of the=
 entries of its diagonal.
</p><p>So, the determinant can be computed for almost free from the result =
of a Gaussian elimination.
</p>
<div class=3D"mw-heading mw-heading3"><h3 id=3D"Decomposition_methods">Deco=
mposition methods</h3><span class=3D"mw-editsection"><span class=3D"mw-edit=
section-bracket">[</span><a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/w/index.php?ti=
